  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How are the types of nerve cell structured?",
  "response": "Nerve cells, or neurons, are specialized cells of the nervous system that transmit signals throughout the body. There are several types of neurons, each with its distinct structure and function:\n\n1. **Sensory Neurons**: \n   - **Structure**: These have long dendrites and short axons. They typically have cell bodies located outside the central nervous system (CNS).\n   - **Function**: They carry signals from sensory receptors to the CNS. Examples include neurons involved in feeling pain, touch, and temperature.\n\n2. **Motor Neurons**: \n   - **Structure**: These neurons have long axons and shorter dendrites. Their cell bodies are located within the CNS.\n   - **Function**: They transmit signals from the CNS to effectors, such as muscles and glands, causing them to react (e.g., muscle contraction).\n\n3. **Interneurons**: \n   - **Structure**: Typically, these have short axons and dendrites. They form connections between other neurons within the CNS.\n   - **Function**: They process information within the brain and spinal cord, facilitating communication between sensory and motor neurons and integrating neural activity.\n\nThe general structure of a neuron includes several key components:\n\n1. **Cell Body (Soma)**: Contains the nucleus and other cellular organelles. It is the metabolic center of the neuron.\n2. **Dendrites**: Branched extensions from the cell body that receive signals from other neurons and transmit them toward the cell body.\n3. **Axon**: A long, slender projection that conducts electrical impulses away from the cell body to other neurons or target tissues.\n4. **Axon Terminals**: The ends of the axon that release neurotransmitters into the synapse (the gap between adjacent neurons) to communicate with other neurons, muscles, or glands.\n5. **Myelin Sheath**: A fatty layer that may cover the axon, insulating it and increasing the speed of signal transmission. This sheath is produced by glial cells (Schwann cells in the peripheral nervous system and oligodendrocytes in the CNS).\n6. **Nodes of Ranvier**: Small gaps in the myelin sheath where the axon membrane is exposed, enabling the rapid transmission of neuronal signals via saltatory conduction.\n\nIn summary, each type of neuron has a specialized structure tailored to its specific role in the nervous system, whether it's transmitting sensory information, motor commands, or integrating signals within the CNS.",
